{{dicdef}}
'''Histolysis''' is the decay and dissolution of organic tissues or of blood. It is sometimes referred to as '''histodialysis'''.<ref>[http://www.yourdictionary.com/histolysis histolysis] at YourDictionary.com. Accessed on 2011-07-09.</ref> In cells, histolysis may be caused by [[uracil|uracil-DNA]] degradation.<ref>{{cite book|title=Progress in Nucleic Acid Research and Molecular Biology, Volume 48|publisher=Academic Press|date=29 September 1994|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kMOY8qD8wd0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=332}}</ref>

Origin: New Latin, from [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|grc|‘ιστος}} (histos) tissue + {{lang|grc|λυσις}} (lusis) dissolution from {{lang|grc|λυειν}} to loosen, dissolve.

