{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = John Jonides | honorific_suffix = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(filename only, i.e. without "File:" prefix)--> | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- if different from "name" --> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|12|08}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!--{{death date and age |YYYY|MM|DD |YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)--> | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | pronounce = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = American | fields = [[Cognitive neuroscience]] | workplaces = [[University of Michigan]] | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[University of Pennsylvania]] (Ph.D., 1975) | thesis_title = Anatomy of an anomaly: The category-effect in visual search | thesis_url = http://psycnet.apa.org/record/1977-30891-001 | thesis_year = 1975 | doctoral_advisor = [[Henry Gleitman]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = | influences = | influenced = | awards = 2011 [[William James Fellow Award]] from the [[Association for Psychological Science]] | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = Linda K. Jonides | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }} '''John Jonides''' (born December 8, 1947)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.umich.edu/~cogneuro/jpg/jjonides.html |title=John Jonides Curriculum Vitae |website=University of Michigan |access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> is an American cognitive neuroscientist and psychologist. He is the [[Edward E. Smith]] Professor of Psychology and Neuroscience at the [[University of Michigan]]. He has been a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] since 1995 and of the [[Society of Experimental Psychologists]] since 1996.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lsa.umich.edu/psych/people/faculty/jjonides.html |title=John Jonides |website=U-M LSA Department of Psychology |language=en |access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref> He is known for his research on the malleability of [[human intelligence]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/22/magazine/can-you-make-yourself-smarter.html |title=Can You Make Yourself Smarter? |last=Hurley |first=Dan |date=2012-04-22 |work=The New York Times Magazine |access-date=2018-07-24 |language=en}}</ref> and on the effects of [[Facebook]] use on [[happiness]] and [[life satisfaction]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2013/08/19/213568763/researchers-facebook-makes-us-sadder-and-less-satisfied |title=Facebook Makes Us Sadder And Less Satisfied, Study Finds |last=Hu |first=Elise |date=2013-08-19 |work=NPR |access-date=2018-07-24 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2015/02/04/383775091/does-facebook-cause-depression-depends-on-how-you-use-it |title=Does Facebook Cause Depression? Depends On How You Use It |last=Chappellet-Lanier |first=Tajha |date=2015-02-04 |work=NPR |access-date=2018-07-24 |language=en}}</ref> In 2011, he received the [[Association for Psychological Science]]'s [[William James Fellow Award]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.psychologicalscience.org/members/awards-and-honors/fellow-award/recipent-past-award-winners/jonides |title=2011 William James Fellow Award |website=Association for Psychological Science |language=en-US |access-date=2018-07-24}}</ref>
